2. Introduction
This final report presents the culmination of our data integration, validation, and visual analytics process. Initially, the core problem statement identified that admissions data was fragmented across four disparate sources, making it difficult to gain a holistic view of the recruitment pipeline. The purpose of this final phase is to present the unified findings derived from the reliable PostgreSQL warehouse and the comprehensive Looker Studio dashboard. This integration successfully tracks the complete student lifecycle—from initial application through outreach, deposit assignment, and immigration compliance—enabling real-time strategic decision-making for Saint Louis University.

3. Project Overview

3.1 Objectives
The primary objective of this project was to unify fragmented data into a single, reliable source of truth. By doing so, the university can transition from merely relying on descriptive statistics to eventually implementing predictive modeling of student success. 
3.2 Data Sources & Structural Definitions
The foundation of this analysis rests on four distinct datasets that were integrated into a master dataset containing over 6,800 application records:
Applicant Data: The primary source for demographics, including Citizenship, Major, and Intake, as well as initial intent.
SEVIS Data: The official record for visa status, providing the sevis_id necessary to validate "Admitted" status.
Connect Data: Internal CRM data used for tracking I-20 progress and initial deposit status.
Outreach Data: Late-funnel data capturing visa approvals and final enrollment status.
To maintain strict audit standards, Reference_ID was utilized as the primary key to link Applicant, Connect, and SEVIS data, while SEVIS_ID served as the relational key to link official government visa records to internal outreach efforts.


3.3 Data Preparation Summary
Transforming the raw CSV files into a functional PostgreSQL database required rigorous cleaning. Key steps included resolving critical scientific notation errors and standardizing Unix timestamp integers into readable datetime formats. Furthermore, text-string "NULL" values were systematically converted into true database NULLs to allow for accurate mathematical aggregations. The integration utilized LEFT JOINS, originating from the Applicant table, to ensure absolute preservation of all records.
